We recommended that the Management:
A.  Direct the AAO and the ERF Handler to conduct dialogues with GSIS to clarify the effectivity period of requests for updating of membership records;
B. Require the AAO to upload the Membership updates within the same month changes occur, pursuant to Items D and C (2) of the GSIS Memorandum Circular No. 027, series of 2021;
C.  Direct the ERF Handler to regularly reconcile with the GSIS to determine the amount of unremitted premiums due for remittances and promptly report discrepancies to the Management;
D. Remit immediately the amount due to the GSIS as a result of the reconciliation to avoid accumulation of unpaid premiums; and
E. Require the OIC-Municipal Accountant to record the appropriate adjustments to reflect the correct ending balance of the Due to GSIS account.

We have recommended that the Management, thru the Local Chief Executive:

a.	Direct all the accountable officers who are in custody of unserviceable properties to return the same to the GSO for the institution of measures for the proper disposal of these properties by the Disposal Committee, in accordance with COA-DBM Joint Circular No. 2024-1 dated January 30, 2024 and Title V of COA Circular No. 92-386 dated October 20, 1992;

b.	Instruct the Designate Accountant to drop from the books the unserviceable properties only upon the grant of specific authority by the COA, after the completion of the disposal procedures as required by the aforementioned Circulars;

c.	Instruct the Designate Accountant to prepare the adjusting entries for the reclassification of the 117 properties amounting to P1,013,890.00 and all other PPE items below the capitalization threshold of P50,000.00 to appropriate Inventory accounts;

d.	Instruct the GSO to cancel the Property Acknowledgement Receipts of the properties below the capitalization threshold and issue an Inventory Custodian Slip in lieu thereof; and

e.	 Require the Inventory Committee to strictly comply with the provisions of COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 for the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances of the Municipality.

We have recommended that the Municipal Mayor require:

The Municipal Treasurer to furnish the Municipal Accountant the certified list of taxpayers, with the amount due and collectible, which would be the basis of the latter, to set-up the RPT/SET Receivables at the beginning of the accounting period;

The Municipal Accountant to accrue real property taxes at the beginning of the year based on the certified list of taxpayers;

The Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Accountant to ensure that all due and demandable taxes be accounted properly in their own records and any delinquent accounts be continuously reported in the books, unless subsequently settled; and

The concerned officials to adhere strictly to the provisions of Section 246 of RA No. 7160 and New Government Accounting System Manual for LGUs, Volume I.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
Require the Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Accountant to reconcile their records in order to establish the proper and accurate amount of RPT and SET Receivables;
Require the Municipal Accountant to prepare Journal Entry Vouchers to record the necessary adjustments as a result of the reconciliation;
Require the Municipal Treasurer to furnish the Municipal Accountant, at the beginning of the year, a duly certified list showing the name of taxpayers and the amount due and collectible for the year which is the basis of the latter to properly set up the RPT and SET Receivables; and
Direct the concerned officials to adhere strictly to the provisions of Section 246 of the Local Government Code and Section 20, Volume I of the New Government Accounting System Manual for LGUs.

