We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the:

a)	Municipal Accountant to record all road networks and its components, based on the Registry of Public Infrastructures, or in its absence, based on the complete Local Road Inventory Report provided with complete description and cost segregation of the road components and provide proper disclosure of the road networks in the Notes to Financial Statements; 

b)	General Service Officer (GSO) to maintain an updated Local Road Inventory and Road Map and keep a complete Local Road Network Property Card of all roads within its area of jurisdiction;

c)	Municipal Engineer to provide the Municipal Accountant and the GSO with the complete description and cost segregation of the components of all roads within its area of jurisdiction;

d)	Inventory Committee to conduct inventory of local roads, highways and bridges within its area of jurisdiction which were acquired thru purchase or construction, donations or transfers without cost.

We recommended, for observance of the Municipality to economy and transparency requisites in government procurements, that the Municipal Mayor being the head of the procuring entity (HoPE) to:

Cause the submission to the Audit Team the contract documents containing the following:

A copy of the approved Bidding Documents intended for sale to prospective bidders prepared in accordance with Section 17 of the RIRR;

A certification issued by the BAC Secretariat that the invitation to bid for each contract was posted in at least three (3) conspicuous places within the Municipality pursuant to Section 21.2.1 of the RIRR;

Direct the Bids and Awards Committee to:

Conduct bid evaluation and post-qualification procedures during the procurement process pursuant to Sections 32 and 34 of the RIRR to ensure award of contract to the responsive and eligible bidders;

Upload the Bidding Documents in the PhilGEPS as required in Section 17.4 of the RIRR to give interested bidders sufficient information about the procurement at hand;

Require the bidders to submit statements of their SLCC, as specified in the Bidding Documents, in compliance with Section 23 of the RIRR so as to ensure that the prospective bidder has the technical and financial capability to undertake the contract;

Prepare minutes of meetings containing the details of the procurement activities and upload the Notice of Award and Notice to Proceed in the PhilGEPS as required in Sections 37.1.6 and 37.4.2 of the RIRR.

We recommended that the Municipality:

Submit a justification for allowing the issuance of fuel to privately owned vehicles and why the subject transactions should not be disallowed in audit;

Stop issuing fuel to privately owned vehicles and ensure that all fuel, oil and lubricant expenses charged to the funds of the Municipality were used exclusively for official purposes and the issuance thereof are in accordance with COA Circular No. 96-004 dated April 19, 1996 to avoid disallowance in audit;

Instruct the concerned officials and employees of the Municipality to charge only the equivalent cost of the customary mode of transportation pursuant to existing laws, rules and regulations;

Advise the officials and employees who are already claiming their monthly Transportation Allowance (TA) and were not issued vehicles to refrain from claiming the customary mode of transportation if the travel is within their official station; and

Stop the grant of fuel and oil and transportation expenses to officials or employees of other government agencies and allow the grant only for the implementation of programs and activities of Municipality that involve their respective agencies, subject to availability of funds and the disbursements thereon should likewise be in accordance with existing laws, rules and regulations.

We recommended that Management:

Direct the Municipal Accountant to support all purchases of drugs and medicines with the required certification of the Municipal Health Officer (MHO) of conformity with PNDF Volume I current edition, to ensure compliance with EO 49;

Instruct the LDRRMO to coordinate with the MHO so as to ensure that medical supplies stockpiled may effectively meet disaster related emergencies.

